[[File:Hotspring Tamagawa Akita 01.jpg|thumb|right|240 px|Naturally discharging source spring ({{ill|Tamagawa Onsen (Akita Prefecture)|ja|玉川温泉|1=Tamagawa Hot Spring|lt=Tamagawa Onsen|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Ōbuki).]]
[[File:Arima Onsen Tenjin Sengen.JPG|thumb|right|180px|Drilled self-discharging source spring ({{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Tenjin Source).]]

'''Source spring''' (源泉, gensen) refers to a location where water emerges from underground. Beyond its literal meaning, the term is used metaphorically to describe the origin of something, such as ideas or monetary sources (e.g., "源泉徴収" or "withholding tax" and "アイデアの源泉" or "the source of ideas").

== Source Springs in Onsen ==
In the context of {{ill|onsen|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|1=Onsen|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a source spring is the location where thermal spring water emerges from underground. There are three main types of spring discharge forms:
* '''Natural discharge:''' Springs that emerge naturally from cracks in the rock or the ground.
* '''Drilled self-discharge:''' Springs that emerge due to pressure after drilling a borehole and installing a pipe.
* '''Drilled powered extraction:''' Springs pumped from deep underground using mechanical power after drilling.

Natural discharge source springs can emerge due to natural phenomena like earthquakes or volcanic eruptions. Drilled springs involve artificial development, often essential for establishing new onsen facilities. In {{ill|Beppu|ja|別府市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōita Prefecture|ja|大分県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, drilling techniques like the {{ill|Kazusa-bori method|ja|上総掘り|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were introduced in 1879 (Meiji 12), leading to the active development of source springs for various uses, including {{ill|onsen ryokan|ja|温泉旅館|qq=draft|qq=draft}} baths, public communal baths, and private residential use. This transformed {{ill|Beppu Onsen|ja|別府温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} into a renowned {{ill|spa town|ja|温泉都市|en|lt=onsen city|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>Beppu has the most source springs (2,847) and the highest daily discharge volume (137,040 kiloliters/day) in Japan (as of 2000, Ministry of the Environment).</ref>

=== Source Springs as Tourist Attractions ===
While many source springs, particularly drilled types, are not open to the public and consist of simple pipes or concrete structures, some have become tourist destinations. These include {{ill|National Places of Scenic Beauty|ja|名勝|qq=draft|qq=draft}} like the four springs of {{ill|Beppu no Jigoku|ja|別府の地獄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ("The Hells of Beppu") and traditional facilities like the {{ill|Myoban Onsen yunohana huts|ja|明礬温泉湯の花小屋|qq=draft|qq=draft}} or {{ill|Kusatsu Onsen|ja|草津温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s {{ill|Yubatake|ja|湯畑|1=Yubatake|2=ja|3=湯畑|4=zh|5=汤畑|6=de|7=Onsen-Felder|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

* '''National Places of Scenic Beauty:'''
** Springs in {{ill|Kannawa Onsen|ja|鉄輪温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Shibaseki Onsen|ja|柴石温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, collectively known as {{ill|Beppu no Jigoku|ja|別府の地獄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, including:
    - {{ill|Umi Jigoku|ja|別府地獄めぐり#海地獄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
    - {{ill|Chinoike Jigoku|ja|別府地獄めぐり#血の池地獄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
    - {{ill|Shiraike Jigoku|ja|別府地獄めぐり#白池地獄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
    - {{ill|Tatsumaki Jigoku|ja|別府地獄めぐり#龍巻地獄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

